<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n37007f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n37" href="#n37007f">N37 (VI.B.28A)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n37all.htm#n37007f"> 7(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Comedy of Ceres </blockquote> <dd class="well"><mm class="note">Note: According to Clark (<cite>The Early Irish Stage. The beginnings to 1720</cite>) Dublin Corporation reputedly entertained in the Christmastide of 1528 the then Lord Deputy with a programme of &lsquo;plays&rsquo;, staged on a platform erected east of the city wall, in Hoggen Green. Among others, the Bakers, in gilded masks and white robes, performed &lsquo;the Comedy of Ceres, the goddess of Corn&rsquo;. According to Gilbert, in the gild plays enacted in late May or early June (at the Corpus Christi festival) in Dublin during the latter half of the fifteenth century&mdash;after the custom of the large towns in the north and west of England&mdash;the Comedy of Ceres, the goddesss of corn, was enacted by the Bakers. </mm> </dd></dl>
